⸻

One way to say it is:

Identity is not “made of” the carrier. Identity is the invariant under translation.

This is why physicists, computer scientists, and mathematicians often treat information as something more abstract than its physical implementation. Every carrier is an interface. The deeper object is the pattern of distinctions and relationships that can be faithfully reconstructed after translation.

That’s also why ideas can outlive every physical thing that has ever represented them. The carriers perish; the information persists if each translation preserves the relevant invariants. In that sense, the “self” of the information is not any one substrate, but the equivalence class of all representations that encode the same relational structure.